msgid "!!! hint \"Package Confusion\""
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/13-softwares.md:533
#, no-wrap
msgid "    The creation of module streams in the AppStream repository caused a lot of people confusion. Since modules are packaged within a stream (see our examples below), a particular package would show up in our RPMs, but if an attempt was made to install it without enabling the module, nothing would happen. Remember to look at modules if you attempt to install a package and it fails to find it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/13-softwares.md:534
#, no-wrap
msgid "What are modules"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/13-softwares.md:537
msgid ""
"Modules come from the AppStream repository and contain both streams and "
"profiles. These can be described as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/13-softwares.md:539
msgid ""
"**module streams:** A module stream can be thought of as a separate "
"repository within the AppStream repository that contains different "
"application versions. These module repositories contain the application "
"RPMs, dependencies, and documentation for that particular stream. An example "
"of a module stream in Rocky Linux 8 would be `postgresql`. If you install "
"`postgresql` using the standard `sudo dnf install postgresql` you will get "
"version 10. However, using modules, you can instead install versions 9.6, 12 "
"or 13."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/13-softwares.md:541
msgid ""
"**module profiles:** What a module profile does is take into consideration "
"the use case for the module stream when installing the package. Applying a "
"profile adjusts the package RPMs, dependencies and documentation to account "
"for the module's use. Using the same `postgresql` stream in our example, you "
"can apply a profile of either \"server\" or \"client\". Obviously, you do "
"not need the same packages installed on your system if you are just going to "
"use `postgresql` as a client to access a server."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/13-softwares.md:542
#, no-wrap
msgid "Listing modules"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/13-softwares.md:545
msgid ""
"You can obtain a list of all modules by executing the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/13-softwares.md:546
#, no-wrap
msgid "dnf module list\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/13-softwares.md:551
msgid ""
"This will give you a long list of the available modules and the profiles "
"that can be used for them. The thing is you probably already know what "
"package you are interested in, so to find out if there are modules for a "
"particular package, add the package name after \"list\". We will use our "
"`postgresql` package example again here:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/13-softwares.md:552
#, no-wrap
msgid "dnf module list postgresql\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/13-softwares.md:557
msgid "This will give you output that looks like this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/13-softwares.md:558
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/13-softwares.md:691
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Rocky Linux 8 - AppStream\n"
"Name                       Stream                 Profiles                           Summary                                            \n"
"postgresql                 9.6                    client, server [d]                 PostgreSQL server and client module                \n"
"postgresql                 10 [d]                 client, server [d]                 PostgreSQL server and client module                \n"
"postgresql                 12                     client, server [d]                 PostgreSQL server and client module                \n"
"postgresql                 13                     client, server [d]                 PostgreSQL server and client module\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/13-softwares.md:568
msgid ""
"Notice in the listing the \"[d]\". This means that this is the default. It "
"shows that the default version is 10 and that regardless of which version "
"you choose, if you do not specify a profile, then the server profile will be "
"the profile used, as it is the default as well."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/13-softwares.md:569
#, no-wrap
msgid "Enabling Modules"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/13-softwares.md:572
msgid ""
"Using our example `postgresql` package, let's say that we want to enable "
"version 12. To do this, you simply use the following:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/13-softwares.md:573
#, no-wrap
msgid "dnf module enable postgresql:12\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/13-softwares.md:578
msgid ""
"Here the enable command requires the module name followed by a \":\" and the "
"stream name."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/13-softwares.md:580
msgid ""
"To verify that you have enabled `postgresql` module stream version 12, use "
"your list command again which should show you the following output:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/13-softwares.md:581
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Rocky Linux 8 - AppStream\n"
"Name                       Stream                 Profiles                           Summary                                            \n"
"postgresql                 9.6                    client, server [d]                 PostgreSQL server and client module                \n"
"postgresql                 10 [d]                 client, server [d]                 PostgreSQL server and client module                \n"
"postgresql                 12 [e]                 client, server [d]                 PostgreSQL server and client module                \n"
"postgresql                 13                     client, server [d]                 PostgreSQL server and client module\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/13-softwares.md:591
msgid ""
"Here we can see the \"[e]\" for \"enabled\" next to stream 12, so we know "
"that version 12 is enabled."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
